**Update 1**
Answering OP&#39;s comment:

&gt;Why don&#39;t I just use bean annotations like @compent,@configuation in MyProperties .Class,and use @Autowired in MyConfig


Basically because `@Configuration` is the place to define beans, its not a bean by itself in a sense that it should be used like a unit that has some business logic of your application. It has happened to be driven by spring for internal reasons, but I suggest to not treat the `@Configuration` classes like regular beans. The same holds for `@ConfigurationProperties` annotated classes: Its a way to load configuration properties / use them in the application. This is more like a &quot;special language&quot; to configure spring related stuff (DSL if you wish). So You can create @Component annotated beans of your business alternatively to the `@Configuration` annotated classes, spring supports both ways of the bean definitions, in in any case you can inject Configuration Properties, however if you want to &quot;plug in&quot; the configuration properties with `@EnableConfigurationProperties` you should use it on a `@Configuration` annotated class.

